    <div xml:id="PN321">
      <lg type="edition" style="pūṭṭuvil">
<l>porippuṟap pūḻiṉ pōrval cēvaṉ</l>
<l>mēntōl kaḷainta tīṅkōḷ veḷḷeṭ</l>
<l>cuḷakiṭai yuṇaṅkaṟ cevvi koṇṭeṉa</l>
<l>vēṉiṟ kōṅkiṉ pūmpokuṭ ṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>kuṭantaiyañ ceviya kōṭṭeli yāṭṭak</l>
<l>kaliyār varakiṉ piṟaṅkupī ḷoḷikkum</l>
<l>vaṉpula vaippi ṉatuvē ceṉṟu</l>
<l>tiṉpaḻam pacīi.... ṉaṉō pāṇa</l>
<l>vāḷvaṭu viḷaṅkiya ceṉṉic</l>
<l>ceruveṅ kuruci lōmpu mūrē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Where, because the cock strong in fighting of the quail with spotted back</l>
<l>took, on the occasion of [it] drying in the winnow,</l>
<l>of the white sesame in sweet bunches from which the upper skin had been removed,</l>
<l>the rat with curved ears, like the pericarps of summerly </l>
<l>Kōṅku flowers, from the [field] ridge gives chase,</l>
<l>[and] it hides in the glistening tender ears of the bulging millet,</l>
<l>it is in the region of hard soil,</l>
<l>the village protected by our quarrelsome lord</l>
<l>with a head that shines with sword scars,</l>
<l>oh bard….</l>
</lg>
    </div>
